<h2>Event in April 2018</h2>
<h3>Warmest April 2018 in many countries</h3>
<br><br>
Temperatures from Central Europe up to Moldova were in April 2018 extremely warm. Many countries (Germany, Czech Republic, Luxembourg, Moldova, and Montenegro) registered the warmest April since their weather analysis begun. Only a few days at the beginning and at the end of the month were about normal or below normal. In Austria it was the warmest April since the year 1800 and the second warmest of the last 251 years. These high temperatures were accompanied by dry air, lower than normal cloud amounts and partly above 50% more sunshine than normal. Therefore in many countries new records of maximum temperature were registered. In some countries the maximum temperature reached more than 30°C at several days. In the Alps the warm weather resulted in rapid snowmelt. At the end of the month the snowmelt in Scandinavia and northern Russia together with rainfall leads to local floods.
<br><br>
In Moldova the number of summer days (maximum temperature above 25°C) are normally 1 to 2 but in this April 3 to 11 summer days were observed. Such indices of extremes (with an overall constant threshold) are not applicable for the different climate conditions occurred in Europe. Therefore percentiles were used to consider these spatial variable conditions. The percentiles were calculated for a five day window centred on each calendar day of a given 30 year climate reference period and for the 90th percentile 10% of the values exceeded this threshold. The TG90p index, days with daily temperature above the 90th percentile (warm days, Figure 1 left) show that this warm spell last for more than 16 days, in many parts even more than 25 days. Therefore this April became the warmest April in many parts from Central Europe to the Black Sea.
The Warm Spell Duration Index (WSDI) (Figure 1, right) indicates that in the northern and southern parts of this anomalous warm region there were more than 10 consecutive days where the temperature was higher than the 90th percentile. The middle part of that region was sometimes interrupted by temperature values below the 90th percentile and therefore the maximum period of consecutive days were only about 6 days.
<br><br>
